<m0>  <m2><ql>
<ql>
<m0>R<m2><ql>
<m0>are is the mother who, upon leaving her baby at day care, doesn't feel a pang of guilt. Depending on our interest in work and our relationship with our children, that pang can pack a walloping punch or merely twinge momentarily.<ep>
  ``I knew my son was going to be OK,'' recalls Barbara Garvine, a teacher who returned to work shortly after her son, now 6, was born. ``But I also used to have this feeling in my stomach that I should be the one doing it for him, that nobody could do it as well as I could. There definitely was the guilt.''<ep>
  Trudging off to the office or the factory, the store or the backroom, we mothers are torn between guilt and necessity. For many, Mom's job is vital to the family's economic well-being. For others, the job is an important source of self-esteem and satisfaction.<ep>
  ``I think we all have this ambivalent feeling, whether we need the job or not,'' explains Susan Lichtman, a businesswoman and Kendall mother of two. ``On one hand, <m1> <m0>you wish you could be there with your children. Then on the other side, you know you can't for whatever reason.''<ep>
  The embers of working mother's guilt <m1> <m0>have been stoked as much by our own feelings as by research and experts who said staying at home with infants was the only way to nurture that one-to-one bonding. With more than half the mothers of young children now employed, according to the U.S. Census Bureau, this debate, often strident, always emotional, gave pause to a nation full of nervous parents.<ep>
  Now, a new, comprehensive report may allay the fears of parents of young children. The five-<m2><ql>
<ql>
