FAMILY MATTERS,  FROM  1F<ql>
<m0>year study of 1,300 families nationwide concluded that infants' trust in their mothers is not compromised by day care (--) as long as a mother is sensitive and responsive to her child.<ep>
  The report, conducted by researchers for the National Institute of Child Health and Human Development, surely must have prompted a collective sigh of relief. It runs counter to earlier research that seemed to show that babies in child care were slightly more likely to have an insecure relationship with their mothers than those whose mothers stayed at home.<ep>
  Needless to say, these old studies alarmed parents, particularly those who had no choice. But this recent report, considered the most far-reaching and comprehensive to date, is being touted as a form of vindication for many mothers who have seen their children thrive in day care.<ep>
<m1>No second thoughts<ep>
<m0>   Jeannie Jontiff, an attorney and mother of a 2-year-old and an 8-month-old, had ``reservations'' about putting Lauren, her eldest, in child care when she was a month old. But when she placed Matthew at a center when he was 3 months old, she harbored no second thoughts. Both children attend Carol Center in downtown Miami, a child care center that prides itself in <m1> <m0>activities for children of all ages.<ep>
  ``So much has to do with the confidence in the people you leave them with,'' says Jontiff, who lives in Morningside. ``I saw how well Lauren did. She's very independent, very adaptable, so I didn't feel guilty with Matthew. I leave him and he's smiling.''<ep>
  Other mothers said the report boosted their confidence and proved what they had been saying all along. Harriet Kamerow of Plantation left both her children (--) now 11 and 14 (--) in day care when they were infants. As a single parent who had to work, she had no choice, but did have enough guilt to go around. Her children's progress, however, stilled her concerns.<ep>
<m1>Too late for her<ep>
<m0>   ``It's nice to see the study, though it's a little late for me,'' Kamerow jokes. ``I think, though, that it will help other mothers, especially the ones who have to work and must put their children in day care.''<ep>
  For most mothers, instinct is really the final word. No study, whether critical or approving, can change strong feelings of wanting to stay home or wanting to return to work.<ep>
  ``It is so individual,'' says Donna Fuhrmann, a Kendall mother of two girls. ``Each child is different and they will do differently in situations. You have to judge by your own experience.''<ep>
  Fuhrmann chose to cut back on her work hours to spend more time with her eldest daughter. Though both girls had been in day care since they were 6 months old, the youngest, now 3, adapted more easily than the oldest.<ep>
  Like other mothers, Fuhrmann believes it is the <m0>quality<m0> of day care that makes all the difference. Top-notch care, more than anything else, helps allay parents' guilt.<ep>
<m1>Some risks<ep>
<m0>   The recent study agrees. Researchers concluded that some aspects of child care appeared to pose risks for vulnerable children. If a mother is not responsive or sensitive to her child's needs, then poor day care, changes of day care several times, or spending more than 10 hours a week in a day-care center can exacerbate the problems in the relationship. However, if the relationship between mother and child is good, the number of hours in day care makes no difference.<ep>
  ``Children are very resilient and they can come back from so much,'' says Garvine, the teacher. ``But we want to be sure they're getting the best when we're not there.''<ep>
